'''Contractualism''' is a term in philosophy that refers either to a family of political theories in the [[social contract]] tradition (when used in this sense, the term is synonymous with [[contractarianism]]),<ref>https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/contractarianism/</ref> or to the ethical theory developed in recent years by [[T. M. Scanlon]], especially in his book ''What We Owe to Each Other''.<ref>https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/contractualism/</ref>
[[Social contract]] theorists from the history of political thought include [[Hugo Grotius]] (1625), [[Thomas Hobbes]] (1651), [[Samuel Pufendorf]] (1673), [[John Locke]] (1689), [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]] (1762), and [[Immanuel Kant]] (1797); more recently, [[John Rawls]] (1971), [[David Gauthier]] (1986) and [[Philip Pettit]] (1997).
