A '''leaf sensor''' is a phytometric device (measurement of [[Plant physiology|plant physiological]] processes<ref>{{cite web | title=Physiological functions characteristic of plants, 2009, National Center for Biological Information (MeSH)| url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/68055639?ordinalpos=7&itool=EntrezSystem2.PEntrez.Mesh.Mesh_ResultsPanel.Mesh_RVDocSum}}</ref>) that measures water loss or the water deficit stress (WDS) in plants<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Cochard H, Coll L, Le Roux X, Améglio T |title=Unraveling the effects of plant hydraulics on stomatal closure during water stress in walnut |journal=Plant Physiol. |volume=128 |issue=1 |pages=282–90 |date=January 2002 |pmid=11788773 |pmc=148995 |doi=10.1104/pp.010400 |url=http://www.plantphysiol.org/cgi/content/full/128/1/282}}</ref> by real-time monitoring the moisture level in plant leaves. The first leaf sensor was developed by LeafSens, an Israeli company granted a [[US patent]] for a mechanical leaf thickness sensing device in 2001.<ref>{{US patent reference |number=6185833 |y=2001 |m=02 |d=13 |inventor=Bravado, B.A., Sharon, Y., Seligmann, R. |title=Leaf thickness sensing device }}</ref> LeafSen has made strides incorporating their leaf sensory technology into citrus orchards in Israel.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Cohen, D. |title=Fruit Drinking |journal=New Scientist |issue=2290 |year=2001| url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg17022903.700-fruitful-drinking.html}}</ref> A solid state smart leaf sensor technology was developed by the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]] for [[NASA]] in 2007. It was designed to help monitor and control [[farm water|agricultural water]] demand.<ref>http://www.colorado.edu/news/releases/2007/244.html</ref> AgriHouse received a [[National Science Foundation]] (NSF) STTR grant in conjunction with the University of Colorado to further develop the solid state leaf sensor technology for precision irrigation control in 2007.<ref>{{cite web | title=AgriHouse Inc. Wins NSF Grant to Develop CU Water Management Technology |publisher=University of Colorado TTO |date=June 7, 2007 | url=https://www.cusys.edu/techtransfer_edit/about/newsreleases/2007/agri_house_cu_water_tech.html}}</ref>
==Precision monitoring==
===Water deficit stress measurements=== [[Image:SG-1000 rev5.jpg|frame|right| AgriHouse Smart Leaf Sensor (SG-1000)]] A Phase I research grant from the National Science Foundation in 2007 showed that the leaf sensor technology has the potential to save between 30% and 50% of irrigation water by reducing irrigation from once every 24 hours to about every 2 to 2.5 days by sensing impending water deficit stress.<ref>{{cite web | title=Turning A New Leaf |publisher=National Science Foundation |date=June 7, 2007 | url=https://www.nsf.gov/news/newsletter/jul_07/NSF_Current_July_2007.pdf}}</ref> Leaf sensor technology developed by AgriHouse indicates water deficit stress by measuring the [[turgor pressure]] of a leaf, which decreases dramatically at the onset of leaf dehydration. Early detection of impending water deficit stress in plants can be used as an input parameter for precision irrigation control by allowing plants to communicate water requirements directly to humans and/or electronic interfaces. For example, a base system utilizing the wirelessly transmitted information of several sensors appropriately distributed over various sectors of a round field irrigated by a center-pivot irrigation system could tell the irrigation lever exactly when and what field sector needs to be irrigated.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Jones, W. |title=New Device Lets Plants Talk: Smart sensors let crops text-message growers for more water |year=2009 |journal=IEEE Spectrum |url=http://www.spectrum.ieee.org/may09/9029}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=M. O'Brien |author2=M. Walton |title=New Leaf Sensor Alerts When Plants Are Thirsty |year=2010|journal=National Science Foundation |url=https://www.nsf.gov/news/special_reports/science_nation/leafsensor.jsp}}</ref>
===Irrigation control=== In a 2008 USDA sponsored field study AgriHouse's SG-1000 Leaf Sensor attached to dry beans demonstrated a 25% savings of irrigation water and pumping cost.<ref>{{cite web | title= AgriHouse awarded exclusive licensing for leaf sensor technology |publisher=Northern Colorado Business Report |date=January 12, 2010 |url=http://ncbr.com/article.asp?id=103724}}</ref> In 2010 the University of Colorado, Boulder, Colorado granted AgriHouse Inc an exclusive license of its patented leaf sensor technology.<ref>{{cite web | title= AgriHouse Inc. Completes Exclusive License for Univ. of Colorado Water Management Technology |publisher=Seed Today |date=January 11, 2010|url=http://www.seedtoday.com/articles/AgriHouse_Inc__Completes_Exclusive_License_for_Univ__of_Colorado_Water_Management_Technology_-88029.html}}</ref>
Precision irrigation monitoring using the SG-1000 leaf sensor and commercial data loggers for irrigation control has been achieved in recent years.<ref>{{cite web | title= Sensors Enable Farmers to Text Messages to Farmers |publisher= NASA Spinoff Publication |date=January 2012|url=http://spinoff.nasa.gov/Spinoff2012/ee_2.html/articles}}</ref> Researchers have found a direct correlation between leaf thickness and Relative Water Content (RWC) of plant leaves using the SG-1000 Leaf Sensor under field conditions.<ref>{{cite web | title= Irrigation control of cowpea plants using the measurement of leaf thickness under greenhouse conditions |publisher= Irrigation Science , Volume 30, Issue 4, pp 247-257|date=July 2012|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00271-011-0268-2/articles}}</ref>
===Water and Energy Conservation=== The agriculture sustainability benefits of water and energy savings have been established using the SG-1000 leaf sensor under field conditions and in greenhouses. Plant science researchers and agronomists have utilized the SG-1000 Leaf Sensor for studying the relationship between water content and leaf cell turgidity potential and leaf thickness. Plant leaf characteristics including water potential and osmotic water potential relationships have been studied with the device.<ref>{{cite journal | title= Leaf thickness and turgor pressure in bean during plant desiccation |journal= Scientia Horticulturae |volume =184| pages= 55–62 |date=5 March 2015|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304423814006980/articles |doi=10.1016/j.scienta.2014.12.025}}</ref>
