{{Infobox anatomy | Name = Lister's tubercle | Latin = tuberculum dorsale | Image = Left_hand_dorsal_view_Arabic_YM.png | Caption = Left hand. Lister's tubercle shown. | Image2 = Real-Time-Magnetic-Resonance-Imaging-(MRI)-during-Active-Wrist-Motion--Initial-Observations-pone.0084004.s002.ogv | Caption2 = Axial T1-weighted MRI slice through the wrist at the level of Lister's tubercle. }} '''Lister's tubercle''' or '''dorsal tubercle of radius''' is a bony prominence located at the distal end of the [[radius (bone)|radius]], palpable on the [[dorsum (anatomy)#human anatomy|dorsum]] of the [[wrist]].
==Function== Lister's [[Tubercle (anatomy)|tubercle]] serves as a pulley for the tendon of [[extensor pollicis longus]], which wraps around the medial side and takes a 45 degree turn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wheelessonline.com/ortho/listers_tubercle|title=Wheeless Online|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref>
